\section*{External anal sphincter}

The EAS comprises of striated muscle and appears red in colour (similar to raw red meat) (Fig. 3.4). As the EAS is normally under tonic contraction, it tends to retract when completely torn. A defect of the EAS can lead to urge faecal incontinence.

\section*{Internal anal sphincter}

The IAS is a thickened continuation of the circular smooth muscle of the bowel and ends with a well-defined rounded edge $6-8 \mathrm{~mm}$ above the anal margin at the junction of the superficial and subcutaneous part of the EAS. In contrast to the EAS, the IAS has a pale appearance to the naked eye (Fig. 3.5). Defect of the IAS can lead to passive soiling of stools and flatus incontinence.

\section*{The longitudinal layer and the conjoint longitudinal coat}

The longitudinal layer is situated between the EAS and IAS and consists of a fibromuscular layer, the conjoint longitudinal coat and the intersphincteric space with its connective tissue components (see Fig. 3.3).

