\section*{Current practice}

National evidence-based guidelines, in relation to antenatal care have been developed and circulated in the UK since 2003. They were updated in 2008 and reviewed again in 2011 when it was decided that there was insufficient new evidence to warrant a change. They are next due for review in 2014.

In addition to full national clinical guidance, NICE also produce 'Quality Standards' that are 'a concise set of statements designed to drive and measure priority quality improvements within a particular area of care' (NICE 2012). The Antenatal Quality Standard comprises 12 statements and these are detailed in Box 10.3. They are a useful framework for examining maternity services and provide benchmarks for audit and commissioning purposes, although most of them relate to women with risk factors.

