\section*{The Rubin manoeuvre}

Rubin (1964) advocated using suprapubic rocking to dislodge the anterior shoulder. If rocking alone proved unsuccessful, vaginal examination (inserting the whole hand) was suggested to identify the most accessible shoulder (usually the posterior shoulder), and push that shoulder in the direction of the fetal chest. This process adducts the shoulders and allows rotation away from the symphysis pubis. The manoeuvre reduces the 12 cm bisacromial diameter (Fig. 22.7).

