Where possible, breastfeeding support from the midwife should always be hands off, but pragmatically, it may be necessary for the midwife to help the mother attach the baby to the breast for the first few feeds. In this case, the midwife should think of her own comfort, as well as that of the mother and the baby. The midwife will put less strain on her own back if she kneels on a foam mat beside the mother, rather than bending over her (see Fig. 34.15).

